==Proto-Indo-European==

===Etymology===
The word {{m|ine-pro||*wĺ̥kʷos}} is a thematic accented zero-grade noun perhaps derived from the adjective {{m|ine-pro|*wl̥kʷós|t=dangerous}}; compare {{cog|hit|𒉿𒀠𒆪𒉿𒀸|tr=walkuwa-|t=something negative}}, {{cog|sga|olc|t=evil}}, {{cog|sa|अवृक|tr=avṛká|t=safe|lit=not wild}}, {{m|sa|वृकतात्|tr=vṛká-tāt|t=savagery}}.<ref>A. Lehrman, “Anatolian Cognates of the PIE Word for ‘Wolf’”, ''Die Sprache'' 33 (1987), 13–18.</ref> Stress shift onto the zero-grade is consistent with nominalized adjectives: compare {{cog|sa|कृष्ण|tr=kṛ́ṣṇa|t=black antelope}} from {{m|sa|कृष्ण|tr=kṛṣṇá|t=black}}. Alternatively, the word may be a derivative of the verbal root {{m|ine-pro|*welh₂-|t=to tear up}}.<ref>Tamaz Gamkrelidze & Vjačeslav Ivanov, ''Indo-European and the Indo-Europeans'' (Tbilisi: Tbilisi UP, 1984), 492.</ref> In either case, the word's formation closely resembles that of {{m|ine-pro|*h₂ŕ̥tḱos|t=bear}}, another thematic accented zero-grade noun whose referent is an animal subject to cultural taboos.<ref>{{R:ine:EIEC|head=*wolf|page=646}}</ref>

The Latin and Greek reflexes are unexpected (vs. expected Lat *''volquus'', Gk *''álpos'', according to the regular progression PIE *''l̥'' > Lat ''ol'', Gk ''al''). The Latin reflex is a borrowing from [[Osco-Umbrian]] (where PIE */kʷ/ regularly gave /p/), and both the Italic and Greek reflexes underwent metathesis, possibly as a taboo deformation meant to offset the fear usually associated with the animal. A deformation would explain the metathesis of */w/ and */l/, which also occurred in Greek ({{m|ine-pro||*wĺ̥kʷos}} → {{m|ine-pro||*lúkʷos}} → {{m|grc|λύκος}}), and also explains the presence of delabialized /k/ per the [[w:boukólos rule|''boukólos'' rule]] (regardless of whether it is Proto-Indo-European already or only Proto-Greek). In both cases, the expected forms are so close to the word for “fox”&nbsp;– compare {{cog|la|volpēs}}, {{cog|grc|ἀλωπός}}, {{m|grc|ἀλώπηξ}}&nbsp;– that avoiding conflation of the two words “wolf” and “fox” may have motivated either alteration or borrowing.

The Germanic reflex, with /f/ < */p/ < */kʷ/, underwent an unusual sound change, but the velar was retained in at least one form, i.&nbsp;e. {{cog|non|ylgr|t=she-wolf}} (vs. {{cog|ang|wylf}}, {{cog|gmh|wülpe}} < {{m|gmw-pro|*wulbi}}) < {{m|gem-pro|*wulgī|*wulgʷī́}} < {{m|ine-pro|*wl̥kʷíh₂s}}.

Armenian and Celtic have replaced the word with {{noncog|ine-pro|*waylos|t=howler}} due to taboo; compare {{cog|xcl|գայլ}}, {{cog|mga|fáel}}.<ref>{{R:xcl:Martirosyan|page=196}}.</ref> (In Celtic, {{m|cel-pro|*kū|t=hound, dog}} is also used to designate the wolf.)

