===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|fyr}}, from {{inh|en|ang|fȳr|t=fire}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*fuir}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*fuïr}}, a regularised form of {{inh|en|gem-pro|*fōr|t=fire}} (compare {{cog|stq|Fjuur}}, {{cog|fy|fjoer}}, {{cog|nl|vuur}}, {{cog|nds|Füer}}, {{cog|de|Feuer}}, {{cog|da|fyr}}), ultimately from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*péh₂wr̥}}.

Compare {{cog|hit|𒉺𒄴𒄯|tr=paḫḫur}}, {{cog|xum|pir}}, {{w|Tocharian}} A/B {{m|xto|por}}/{{m|txb|puwar}}, {{cog|cs|pýř|t=hot ashes}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|πῦρ|t=fire}}, and {{cog|hy|հուր|t=fire}}). This was an inanimate noun whose animate counterpart was {{cog|ine-pro|*h₁n̥gʷnis}} (see ''[[ignite]]''). Cognate to {{doublet|notext=1|en|pyre}}.

