====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{senseid|en|Q3196}}{{lb|en|uncountable}} A (usually self-sustaining) [[chemical]] [[reaction]] involving the [[bond]]ing of [[oxygen]] with [[carbon]] or other [[fuel]], with the production of [[heat]] and the presence of [[flame]] or [[smolder|smouldering]].
# {{lb|en|countable}} An instance of this chemical reaction, especially when intentionally created and maintained in a specific location to a useful end (such as a [[campfire]] or a [[hearth]] fire).
#: {{ux|en|We sat about the '''fire''' singing songs and telling tales.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1913|author={{w|Joseph C. Lincoln}}|chapter=8
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5535161W Mr. Pratt's Patients]
|passage=We toted in the wood and got the '''fire''' going nice and comfortable. Lord James still set in one of the chairs and Applegate had cabbaged the other and was hugging the stove.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} The occurrence, often [[accidental]], of fire in a certain place, causing damage and danger.
#: {{ux|en|There was a '''fire''' at the school last night and the whole place burned down.}}
#: {{ux|en|During hot and dry summers many '''fires''' in forests are caused by regardlessly discarded cigarette butts.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=January 1, 2020|issue=73,044|page=24|author=Bernard Lagan|title=Thousands flee to beaches as the flames close in|work=The Times|passage=Efforts to fight the '''fires''' in New South Wales and Victoria were hampered as large '''fires''' converged and created their own violent weather systems. The '''fire''' created dry lightning storms so severe that planes had to be grounded.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|alchemy|philosophy}} The aforementioned chemical reaction of burning, considered one of the [[w:Classical_element|Classical elements]] or basic elements of alchemy.
# {{lb|en|countable|British}} A [[heater]] or [[stove]] used in place of a real fire (such as an [[electric fire]]).
# {{lb|en|countable}} The elements necessary to start a fire.
#: {{ux|en|The '''fire''' was laid and needed to be lit.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[bullet]]s or other [[projectile]]s fired from a [[gun]] or other [[ranged weapon]].
#: {{ux|en|The '''fire''' from the enemy guns kept us from attacking.}}
# {{lb|en|rocketry}} An instance of [[#Verb|firing]] one or more [[rocket]] [[engine]]s.
#: {{ux|en|[[static fire|static '''fire''']]}}
# Strength of passion, whether love or hate.
#* {{RQ:Atterbury Luther}}
#*: He had '''fire''' in his temper.
# Liveliness of imagination or fancy; intellectual and moral enthusiasm.
#* {{RQ:Pope Essay on Criticism|passage=And bless their critic with a poet's '''fire'''.}}
# [[splendour|Splendour]]; [[brilliancy]]; [[lustre]]; hence, a [[star]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|act=I|scene=iv|passage=Stars, hide your '''fires'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=12|passage=As in a zodiac representing the heavenly '''fires'''.}}
# A [[severe]] [[trial]]; anything inflaming or provoking.
# Red [[coloration]] in a piece of [[opal]].

