{{head|la|prefix}}

# {{non-gloss definition|Used in compounds to indicate a being or bringing together of several objects}}
#: {{m|la|coeo|'''co'''eō}}, {{m|la|colloquor|'''col'''loquor}}, {{m|la|convivor|'''con'''vīvor}}, etc.: {{m|la|colligo|'''col'''ligō}}, {{m|la|compono|'''com'''pōnō}}, {{m|la|condo|'''con'''dō}}, etc.
# {{non-gloss definition|Used in compounds to indicate the completeness, perfecting of any act, and thus gives intensity to the signification of the simple word}}
#: {{m|la|commaculo|'''com'''maculō}}, {{m|la|commendo|'''com'''mendō}}, {{m|la|concito|'''con'''citō}}, {{m|la|comminuo|'''com'''minuō}}, {{m|la|concerpo|'''con'''cerpō}}, {{m|la|concido|'''con'''cīdō}}, {{m|la|convello|'''con'''vellō}}, etc.

====Usage notes====
* Before vowels and ''h'', the prefix becomes {{m|la|co-}}, or rarely {{m|la|com-}}. Excluded are ''i'' and ''u'' when these represent {{IPAchar|/j/}} and {{IPAchar|/w/}}.
* Before ''b'', ''m'' and ''p'', the prefix becomes {{m|la|com-}}.
* Before ''l'', the prefix becomes {{m|la|col-}}.
* Before ''r'', the prefix becomes {{m|la|cor-}}.
* Before ''n'', the prefix becomes {{m|la|cō-}} (or remains {{m|la||con-}}, in [[Late Latin]]).
* Before original ''gn'', the prefix becomes {{m|la|co-}} and ''gn'' is not reduced to ''n''.

As usual in Latin phonology, the sequences ''ons'' and ''onf'' are pronounced with nasalised long vowels, and the vowel is written with a macron, i.e. {{m|la|cōnspīrō}} and {{m|la|cōnferō}}.

