==Proto-Indo-European==

===Etymology===
From {{suf|ine-pro|*dʰeǵʰ-|*ōm}}.

However, Kloekhorst argues that the Sanskrit and Anatolian evidence point towards a reconstruction of the root {{m|ine-pro|*dʰeǵ-}} as opposed to ''*dʰeǵʰ-'' on the basis that:
# In the Sanskrit oblique stem jm-, -j- must reflect *ǵ-, and cannot reflect *ǵʰ-, which would regularly give -h- in all positions.
# The long vowel in the Hittite nom. sg. [tēkan] suggests a "voiced unaspirated" (pre-glottalised) velar. See [http://www.kloekhorst.nl/KloekhorstPleneE.pdf Kloekhorst (2012)].
# The *ǵʰ- reconstructable from Latin, Germanic and Greek can be explained in the glottalic theory as a simplification of the cluster *dʰǵ /dˀɡ/ to *dʰǵʰ /dɡ/. The opposite development is much less likely. <br />

It should be noted, however, that the glottalic theory is not generally accepted.

A phonetically difficult but possible connection is with {{m|ine-pro|*(s)teg-|*(s)teǵ-|to cover}}, with devoicing of ''*dʰ'' to ''*t'' via {{w|Siebs' law}}.<ref>{{R:ine:Kortlandt:2014}}</ref>

===Noun===
{{ine-noun|f}}<ref>{{R:gem:PIEPG}}</ref>

# {{topics|ine-pro|Earth}} [[earth]]
# [[human]]

====Inflection====
According to Ringe:
{{ine-decl-noun-mf|ac=amphikinetic|n=s|dʰéǵʰom|ǵʰm̥|loc_sg=ǵʰém}}
Notes:
* Nom. from **dʰéǵʰoms
* Acc. from **dʰéǵʰomm̥

The Hittite evidence suggests a regular hysterokinetic inflection; Kloekhorst reconstructs the original paradigm as:
: Nom. sg.  *dʰéǵ-m- <br />
: Acc. sg.  *dʰǵ-ém-m <br />
: Gen. sg.  *dʰǵ-m-és <br />

