===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|enm|fede}}, {{m|enm|fed}}, from the verb (see above).

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[food|Food]] given to (especially [[herbivorous]]) animals.
#: {{ux|en|They sell '''feed''', riding helmets, and everything else for horses.}}
# Something [[supply|supplied]] continuously.
#: {{ux|en|a satellite '''feed'''}}
# The part of a machine that supplies the material to be operated upon.
#: {{ux|en|the paper '''feed''' of a printer}}
# The forward motion of the material fed into a machine.
# {{lb|en|UK|Australia|New Zealand|colloquial|countable}} A [[meal]].
#* '''184?''', Henry Mayhew, ''London Labour and the London Poor''
#*: One proposed going to Hungerford-market to do a '''feed''' on decayed shrimps or other offal laying about the market; another proposed going to Covent-garden to do a '[[tightener]]' of rotten oranges, to which I was humorously invited; {{...}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1898|author=H.G. Wells|authorlink=H.G. Wells|title={{w|The War of the Worlds}}|publisher=William Heinemann|location=London|page=257|passage="There won't be any more blessed concerts for a million years or so; there won't be any Royal Academy of Arts, and no nice little '''feeds''' at restaurants."}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A gathering to eat, especially in quantity.
#: {{ux|en|They held a crab '''feed''' on the beach.}}
# {{lb|en|Internet}} Encapsulated [[online]] [[content]], such as [[news]] or a [[blog]], that can be [[subscribe]]d to.
#: {{ux|en|I've subscribed to the '''feeds''' of my favourite blogs, so I can find out when new posts are added without having to visit those sites.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Mike Isaac|title=Instagram May Change Your Feed, Personalizing It With an Algorithm|work=The New York Times|date=2016-03-15|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/16/technology/instagram-feed.html|issn=0362-4331|passage=Refresh the top of your various “'''feeds'''” — the running column of content on some versions of Facebook, Twitter and Instagram — and you will see the latest news at the top. The further back you scroll, the older the material gets.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Charlie Warzel|title=What Facebook Fed the Baby Boomers|work=The New York Times|date=2020-11-24|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/24/opinion/facebook-disinformation-boomers.html|issn=0362-4331|passage=Despite spending years studying these toxic dynamics and the better part of a month watching them up close in strangers’ '''feeds''', I was still, like so many, surprised to see it all reflected at the ballot box. We shouldn’t have been surprised; our divisions have been in front of our faces and inside our '''feeds''' this whole time.}}
# A [[straight man]] who delivers lines to the [[comedian]] during a performance.
#* '''2020''', Oliver Double, ''Alternative Comedy: 1979 and the Reinvention of British Stand-Up'' (page 38)
#*: Don Ward is often described as a former comic, having some experience in this area as a young man, acting as a '''feed''' for the comic actor David Lodge at Parkins Holiday Camp in Jersey {{...}}

