# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[hide]], or cause to hide, in the earth; to chase into a [[burrow]] or [[den]].
#* {{RQ:Dryden Spanish Fryar|48|{{...}}the Fox is '''earth’d''',{{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1819|author=John Mayer|title=The Sportsman's Directory, or Park and Gamekeeper's Companion|passage=This is the time that the horseman are flung out, not having the cry to lead them to the death. When quadruped animals of the venery or hunting kind are at rest, the stag is said to be harboured, the buck lodged, the fox kennelled, the badger '''earthed''', the otter vented or watched, the hare formed, and the rabbit set.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[burrow]].
#*{{quote-book|en|a. 1740|{{w|Thomas Tickell}}|Fragment on Hunting|passage=foxes '''earth'd'''}}

