===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{senseid|en|stuff}} Physical [[matter]]; [[material]].
#* '''1699''', {{w|Sir William Temple, 1st Baronet|William Temple}}, ''[http://essays.quotidiana.org/temple/heads_for_conversation/ Heads designed for an essay on conversations]''
#*: Study gives strength to the mind; conversation, grace: the first apt to give stiffness, the other suppleness: one gives '''substance''' and form to the statue, the other polishes it.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1834|author={{w|Letitia Elizabeth Landon}}|title=Francesca Carrara|volume=2|page=308|text=His wasted hands were stretched out, and worked with a quick and convulsive motion, as if catching some small '''substances''' which kept eluding their grasp;...}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-07-20|volume=408|issue=8845|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/science-and-technology/21581981-what-pollution-some-opportunity-others-welcome-plastisphere Welcome to the plastisphere]
|passage=Plastics are energy-rich '''substances''', which is why many of them burn so readily. Any organism that could unlock and use that energy would do well in the Anthropocene. Terrestrial bacteria and fungi which can manage this trick are already familiar to experts in the field.}}
#: {{syn|en|matter|stuff}}
## {{senseid|en|homogeneous}} A form of matter that has constant chemical composition and characteristic properties.
##: {{cot|en|compound|element|mixture|composite}}
# The [[essential]] part of anything; the most vital part.
#* {{RQ:Dryden Annus Mirabilis|passage=Heroic virtue did his actions guide, / And he the '''substance''', not the appearance, chose.}}
#* {{RQ:Burnet Earth}}
#*: This edition is the same in '''substance''' with the Latin.
#* '''1796''', {{w|Edmund Burke}}, ''{{w|Letters on a Regicide Peace}}''
#*: It is insolent in words, in manner; but in '''substance''' it is not only insulting, but alarming.
#: {{syn|en|crux|gist}}
# Substantiality; solidity; firmness.
#: {{ux|en|Some textile fabrics have little '''substance'''.}}
# Material possessions; estate; property; resources.
#: {{ux|en|a man of '''substance'''}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|Luke|15|13}}
#*: And there wasted his '''substance''' with riotous living.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Comedy of Errors|act=I|scene=i|passage=Thy '''substance''', valued at the highest rate, / Cannot amount unto a hundred marks.}}
#* {{RQ:Swift Conduct of the Allies|page=26|passage=And as we have waſted our Strength and vital '''Subſtance''' in this profuſe manner, ſo we have ſhamefully miſapplied it to Ends at leaſt very different from thoſe for which we undertook the War, and often to effect others which after a Peace we may ſeverely repent.}}
# [[drug|Drugs]] {{gloss|illegal narcotics}}
#: {{ux|en|'''substance''' abuse}}
#: {{syn|en|dope|gear}}
# {{lb|en|theology}} [[hypostasis|Hypostasis]].

