===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fr|oxygène}} (originally in the form ''principe oxygène'', a variant of ''principe oxigine'' ‘acidifying principle’, suggested by {{w|Lavoisier}}), from {{der|en|grc|ὀξύς|t=sharp}} + {{m|grc|γένος|t=birth}}, referring to oxygen's supposed role in the formation of acids.
{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂eḱ-}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|ŏk'sĭjən}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈɒksɪdʒən/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-oxygen.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{senseid|en|Q629}}The chemical [[element]] (''symbol'' O) with an [[atomic number]] of 8 and [[relative atomic mass]] of 15.9994. It is a [[colorless]] and [[odorless]] [[gas]]. [[Category:en:Oxygen]]
#: {{hypernyms|en|chalcogen}}
# Molecular oxygen (O<sub>2</sub>), a [[colorless]], [[odorless]] gas at room temperature, also called [[dioxygen]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=September-October|author=[http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/katie-l-burke Katie L. Burke]
|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/pub/2013/5/in-the-news-47 In the News]
|passage='''Oxygen''' levels on Earth skyrocketed 2.4 billion years ago, when cyanobacteria evolved photosynthesis: the ability to convert water and carbon dioxide into carbohydrates and waste '''oxygen''' using solar energy. The evolutionary precursor of photosynthesis is still under debate, and a new study sheds light.}}
# {{lb|en|medicine}} A mixture of oxygen and other gases, administered to a patient to help them [[breathe]].
# {{lb|en|countable}} An [[atom]] of this element.
#* '''2013''', Spencer L. Seager, Michael R. Slabaugh, ''Chemistry for Today: General, Organic, and Biochemistry'' (page 479)
#*: Look first at any structure to see if there is a carbon with two '''oxygens''' attached. Hemiacetals, hemiketals, acetals, and ketals are all alike in that regard.
# {{lb|en|figurative}} A condition or environment in which something can thrive.
#: ''Silence is the '''oxygen''' of shame.''
#: ''They hoped to starve the terrorists of the '''oxygen''' of publicity.''

