# An advanced or leading position; the lookout.
#* {{RQ:Fuller Church History}}
#*: Wolsey sat at the '''stem''' more than twenty years.
# {{lb|en|botany}} The above-ground [[stalk]] (''technically'' [[axis]]) of a vascular [[plant]], and certain anatomically similar, below-ground [[organ]]s such as [[rhizome]]s, [[bulb]]s, [[tuber]]s, and [[corm]]s.
#* '''1736''', Sir {{w|Walter Raleigh}}, ''The History of the World in Five Books''
#*: After they are shot up thirty feet in length, they spread a very large top, having no bough nor twig in the trunk or the '''stem'''.
# A [[slender]] supporting member of an individual part of a plant such as a flower or a leaf; also, by analogy, the shaft of a feather.
#: {{ux|en|the '''stem''' of an apple or a cherry}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=May-June|author=[http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/william-e-conner-1 William E. Conner]| title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2013/3/an-acoustic-arms-race An Acoustic Arms Race]| volume=101| issue=3| page=206-7| magazine={{w|American Scientist}}| passage=Earless ghost swift moths become “invisible” to echolocating bats by forming mating clusters close (less than half a meter) above vegetation and effectively blending into the clutter of echoes that the bat receives from the leaves and '''stems''' around them.}}
# {{senseid|en|narrow part}} A narrow part on certain man-made objects, such as a [[wine glass]], a tobacco pipe, a spoon.
# {{senseid|en|grammar}}{{lb|en|linguistics}} The main part of an [[inflection|uninflected]] word to which [[affix]]es may be added to form inflections of the word. A stem often has a more fundamental [[root]]. Systematic [[conjugation]]s and [[declension]]s derive from their stems.
# {{lb|en|slang}} A person's [[leg]].
#* '''2008''', Lori Wilde, Rhonda Nelson, Cara Summers, ''August Harlequin Blaze''
#*: She was perfectly, fuckably proportioned everywhere else, both above and below her waist. A pocket-size Venus, with the longest '''stems''' he'd ever seen on someone so dang diminutive.
# {{lb|en|slang}} The [[penis]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2005|author=Eric Bogosian|title=Wasted Beauty|page=135|passage=Waves of ecstasy roll through him as the moustachioed Casanova slides his '''stem''' in and out of the spaced-out chick.}}
# {{lb|en|typography}} A vertical stroke of a letter.
# {{lb|en|music}} A vertical stroke marking the length of a note in written music.
#: {{syn|en|tail|virgula|q2=obsolete}}
# {{lb|en|music}} A premixed portion of a track for use in audio mastering and remixing.
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Karl Pedersen|title=The Recording, Mixing, and Mastering Reference Handbook|year=2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=268|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=y9B2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA268&dq=stem+mixing&hl=&cd=2&source=gbs_api#v=onepage&q=stem%20mixing&f=false|isbn=978-0-19-068663-5|author2=Mark Grimshaw-Aagaard|passage='''Stem''' mastering processes a mix by breaking it down into several manageable pieces—that is, stereo '''stems'''. The '''stem''' approach allows the mastering engineer the opportunity to make larger or smaller changes to separate mix elements before the final compression and limiting are applied to the complete mix.}}
# {{lb|en|nautical}} The vertical or nearly vertical forward extension of the [[keel]], to which the forward ends of the planks or [[strake]]s are attached.
#* {{RQ:Marlowe Tamburlaine|1|I|ii|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0HFGOmnsvAMC&pg=PP26|Both we will walke vpon the loftie cliffes,<br>And Chriſtian Merchants that with Ruſſian '''ſtems'''<br>Plow vp huge furrowes in the Caſpian ſea,<br>Shall vaile to vs, as Lords of al the Lake.}}
# {{lb|en|cycling}} A component on a bicycle that connects the [[handlebar]]s to the bicycle fork.
