#*::: The Irish used in Munster isn’t the same as our Irish.

===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|ga|sga|is||is}}, ultimately from {{der|ga|ine-pro|*h₁es-||to be}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|ga|/ɪsˠ/|/sˠ/}} {{qualifier|before nouns and adjectives}}
* {{IPA|ga|/ʃ/}} {{qualifier|before the pronouns {{m|ga|é}}, {{m|ga|í}}, {{m|ga|ea}}, {{m|ga|iad}}}}

====Particle====
{{head|ga|particle}}

# {{non-gloss definition|Present/future realis copula form}}
#: {{ux|ga|'''Is''' múinteoir é Dónall.|Dónall is a teacher.|inline=1}} {{qualifier|definition: predicate is indefinite}}
#: {{ux|ga|'''Is''' é Dónall an múinteoir.|Dónall is the teacher.|inline=1}} {{qualifier|identification: predicate is definite}}
#: {{ux|ga|'''Is''' féidir liom snámh.|I can swim.|inline=1}} {{qualifier|idiomatic noun predicate}}
#: {{ux|ga|'''Is''' maith liom tae.|I like tea.|inline=1}} {{qualifier|idiomatic adjective predicate}}
#: {{ux|ga|'''Is''' mise a chonaic é.|I'm the one who saw him.|inline=1}} {{qualifier|compare Hiberno-English "'Tis I who saw him"; cleft sentence}}
#: {{ux|ga|'''Is''' é Dónall atá ina mhúinteoir.|It's Dónall who is a teacher.|inline=1}} {{qualifier|cleft sentence}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to introduce the comparative/superlative form of adjectives}}
#: {{ux|ga|an buachaill '''is''' mó|the bigger boy; the biggest boy|inline=1}}
#: {{ux|ga|'''Is''' mó an buachaill ná Séamas.|The boy is bigger than James.}}
#: {{ux|ga|Is é Séamas an buachaill '''is''' mó in Éirinn!|James is the biggest boy in Ireland! (''lit.'' "It is James (who is) the boy (who) is biggest in Ireland")}}

=====Usage notes=====
* Used in the present and future for identification or definition of a subject as the person/object identified in the predicate of the sentence. Sometimes used with noun or adjective predicates, especially in certain fixed idiomatic phrases. Used to introduce [[w:cleft sentence|cleft sentences]], which are extremely common in Irish. It is not a verb.

* The copula does not exist in the imperative and does not have a nominal form analogous to the verbal noun.  The phrase {{m|ga|bí}} {{m|ga|i}} {{m|ga|do}} (literally “be in your”) is used as the imperative instead (e.g. ''Bí i d’fhear!'' – “Be a man!” (lit. “Be in your man!”)), and equivalent non-copular nominal constructions must be used in place of their hypothetical copular equivalents: {{m|ga|bheith}} {{m|ga|ábalta}} (“to be able”, in place of the non-existent nominal form of {{m|ga|is féidir}}), {{m|ga|bheith}} {{m|ga|ag}} {{m|ga|iarraidh}} (“to want”, in place of the non-existent nominal form of {{m|ga|is mian le|is mian}}), {{m|ga|bheith}} {{m|ga|ina}} (“to be”, as with the imperative), etc.

* In comparative/superlative formations, ''is'' is strictly speaking the relative of the copula, hence ''an buachaill is mó'' literally means "the boy who is biggest", i.e. "the biggest boy". The thing compared is introduced by {{m|ga|ná||than}}.

