==Proto-Indo-European==

===Etymology===
From {{m|ine-pro|*h₁engʷ-|t=to burn; fire}}.

===Noun===
{{ine-noun|m}}

# {{topics|ine-pro|Fire}} [[fire]]
#: {{syn|ine-pro|*péh₂wr̥}}

====Usage notes====
Two main terms for “fire” are reconstructible for Proto-Indo-European: {{m|ine-pro||*h₁n̥gʷnis}} and {{m|ine-pro|*péh₂wr̥}}. They are usually considered in semantic opposition. The first term is usually masculine and refers to fire as something animate and active (compare {{m|en|Agni}}, the most prominent Old Indic deity), whereas the second term is neuter and refers to fire as something inanimate and passive, i.e. as a substance.

