|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5535161W Mr. Pratt's Patients]
|passage=Pretty soon I struck into a sort of path&nbsp;[&hellip;]. It twisted and turned,{{...}}and opened out into a big clear space like a lawn. And, back of the lawn, was a big, old-fashioned house, with piazzas stretching in front of it, and all '''blazing''' with lights.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|poetic}} To be conspicuous; shine brightly a brilliancy {{q|of talents, deeds, etc.}}.
# {{lb|en|transitive|rare}} To set in a blaze; [[burn]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause to [[shine]] forth; [[exhibit]] vividly; be [[resplendent]] with.
# {{lb|en|transitive|only in the past participle}} To mark with a white spot on the face {{q|as a horse}}.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To set a mark on {{q|as a tree, usually by cutting off a piece of its bark}}.
#* {{RQ:Doyle Lost World|passage=We drew them up, therefore, and concealed them among the bushes, '''blazing''' a tree with our axes, so that we should find them again.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To indicate or mark out {{q|a [[trail]], especially through vegetation}} by a series of blazes.
#: {{ux|en|The guide '''blazed''' his way through the undergrowth.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|figurative}} To set a [[precedent]] for the [[take on|taking-on]] of a challenge; [[lead by example]].
#: {{ux|en|Darwin '''blazed''' a path for the rest of us.}}
# {{lb|en|figurative}} To be furiously angry; to speak or write in a rage.
