==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{q|usually}} {{IPA|en|/ən/|/n̩/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl--en.wav |Audio (Southern England)}}
* In many accents, ''-en'' routinely gives up its vowel syllable when given additional suffixes. For example, {{m|en|fatten}} {{IPAchar|/ˈfæt.n̩/}} + {{m|en|-ing}} {{IPAchar|/-ɪŋ/}} can be {{IPAchar|/ˈfæt.n̩.ɪŋ/}} or {{IPAchar|/ˈfæt.nɪŋ/}}.
** Even in many accents where this habitual syllable deletion is less usual, the syllable loss may still predominate for certain inflections that have become common words in their own right, such as {{m|en|gardener}} {{IPAchar|/ɡɑː(ɹ)d.nə(ɹ)/}}.
** Syllable loss may be habitually prevented to avoid merging with more deeply entrenched inflections, such as for keeping the generic inflection {{m|en|lightening}} {{IPAchar|/ˈlaɪt.n̩.ɪŋ/}} from being pronounced identically to the established term {{m|en|lightning}} {{IPAchar|/ˈlaɪt.nɪŋ/}} (notice the ''e'' is no longer written), even if they both independently derived from a combination of {{m|en|lighten}} + {{m|en|-ing}}.
*** But syllable loss may resume with inflections that are not in danger of merging with an established word, such as {{m|en|enlightening}}, which can be pronounced {{IPAchar|/ɛnˈlaɪt.n̩.ɪŋ/}} or {{IPAchar|/ɛnˈlaɪt.nɪŋ/}} because {{m|en|enlightning}} is not a common word outside of slang.

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|-n}}, {{m|enm|-en}}, past participle ending of [[strong verb]]s (compare {{cog|enm|[[take]](n), [[took]], [[taken]]||take, took, taken}}), from {{bor|en|non|-inn}}, past participle ending of strong verbs (compare {{cog|non|[[taka]], [[tók]], [[tekinn]]||take, took, taken}}). From {{der|en|gmq-pro|*-ᛁᚾᚨ-||tr=*-ina-}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*-inaz}}, a variant of {{m|gem-pro|*-anaz}}. Replaced the native past participle ending of strong verbs (from {{cog|ang|-en}}) in some words, which had weakened to ''-e'' or disappeared (compare Southern {{cog|enm|[[do]](n), [[dud]](e), [[ydo]]||do, did, done}}), but not in others (compare {{m|enm|[[cume]](n), [[com]], [[ycume]]||come, came, come}}), from {{der|en|gem-pro|*-anaz}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*-nós}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alt|en|-n}}

====Suffix====
{{en-suffix|cat2=inflectional suffixes}}

# {{lb|en|no longer productive}} {{non-gloss definition|Denotes the [[past participle]] form when attached to a verb.}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|take|taken}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|forgive|forgiven}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|prove|proven}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Denotes a quasi-past participle or participle-like adjective when attached to a noun or verb.}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|fork|forken|gloss2=forked}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|pave|paven|gloss2=paved}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|barefoot|bare-footen|gloss2=bare-footed}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|enslave|enslaven|gloss2=enslaved}}

=====Usage notes=====
Some linguistic writing on English, such as ''The Oxford Dictionary of English Grammar'', uses ''-en'' as the name of an abstract [[morpheme]] which forms the past participle of all English verbs, even those which do not actually contain the suffix ''-en'', such as {{m|en|cook}} + {{m|en|-en}} → {{m|en|cooked}}.

