===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|enm|-en}}, from {{inh|en|ang|-an}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*-an-}}, {{m|gem-pro|*-in-}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*-én-}}.

From {{inh|en|enm|-n}} (in words ending in a vowel: ''flee: fleen'' "flea: fleas") and '''-en'''. Noun plural marker (predominantly in Southern dialects of {{m|en|Middle English}}), from {{m|en|Old English}} nominative-accusative plural ending of [[w:Old English grammar#n-stems|weak nouns]] (n-stem declension); compare {{suffixusex|ang|nama|g1=m|t1=name|naman|t2=names}}; {{suffixusex|ang|hlǣfdīġe|g1=f|t1=lady|hlǣfdīġan|t2=ladies}}; {{suffixusex|ang|ēare|g1=n|t1=ear|ēaran|t2=ears}}. Assisted by Middle English dative plural ending '''-n''', '''-en''' from late O.E. ''-un, -on'', weakened form of earlier {{m|ang|-um}}. Akin to {{cog|goh|-}} n-stem (compare ''namo: namon'' "name: names"), Latin n-stem (compare ''homo: homin-'')

