==German==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|de|gmh|-en}}, a merger of various terminations in {{inh|de|goh|-}} reflecting different conjugational patterns, namely {{m|goh|-an}}, {{m|goh|-ōn}}, {{m|goh|-en}} ({{m|goh|-ien}}), and {{m|goh|-nen}}, from {{der|de|gem-pro|*-aną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*-ōną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*-janą}}, {{m|gem-pro|*-āną}}, and {{m|gem-pro|*-naną}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alt|de|-n||after ''-er, -el''; in {{m|de|Herrn}}, {{m|de|sein}}, {{m|de|tun}}, and some dated/poetic/colloquial forms such as {{m|de|gehn}}, {{m|de|stehn}}}}
* {{alt|de|-'n||alternatively in the dated/poetic/colloquial forms}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|de|/ən/}}
** {{IPA|de|[ən]}} {{q|possible in all contexts, but rare in most regions}}
** {{IPA|de|[m̩]}} {{q|after labial stops and sometimes labial nasals and fricatives}}
** {{IPA|de|[ŋ̍]}} {{q|after velar stops and sometimes velar nasals and fricatives}}
** {{IPA|de|[l̩n]}} {{q|with ''-l-'' after a full vowel}}
** {{IPA|de|[ɐn]}} {{q|with ''-r-'' after a full vowel}}
** {{IPA|de|[n̩]}} {{q|otherwise}}

====Suffix====
{{head|de|suffix|cat2=verb-forming suffixes|cat3=inflectional suffixes}}

# {{ngd|A suffix of verbs in their [[Appendix:Glossary#infinitive|infinitive]] form.}}
#: Accordingly, the suffix is also applied to verbs borrowed from other languages, and may be understood as the suffix for denominal verbs in general (actually {{m|de|-∅}} derivation or [[conversion]] plus an inflectional suffix that happens to be part of the [[citation form]] of a German verb).
#:: {{suffixusex|de|Foul|foulen|gloss2= to foul}}
#:: {{uxi|de|managen|to manage}}
# {{ngd|A suffix indicating the 1st and 3rd person plural forms (except the present indicative {{m|de|sind}} of {{m|de|sein}}).}}
#: {{uxi|de|wir kommen|we arrive}}
#: {{uxi|de|sie kommen|they arrive}}
# {{ngd|A suffix appended to strong verb stems to form the past participle, usually together with {{m|de|ge-}}.}}
#: {{m|de|fallen}} + {{m|de|ge-}} and ''-en'' → {{m|de|gefallen}}

===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|de|gmh|-en}}, a merger of various terminations in {{inh|de|goh|-}} reflecting different [[Appendix:Glossary#declension|declensional]] patterns.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alt|de|-n||after ''-er, -el'' in nouns, but not usually in adjectives}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|de|/ən/}} {{q|variants as in etymology 1}}

====Suffix====
{{head|de|suffix|cat2=inflectional suffixes}}

# {{non-gloss definition|A suffix appended to some nouns in all of their plural forms. These nouns are so-called “weak” or “mixed” nouns; they are most often feminine, often masculine, rarely neuter.}}
# {{non-gloss definition|A suffix appended to weak masculine nouns in all [[oblique]] cases of the singular, and to some mixed nouns in the singular dative and accusative}}
# {{non-gloss definition|A suffix appended to most other nouns, the so-called “strong” nouns, in their plural dative}}
# {{non-gloss definition|A suffix (in fact, the most common declensional ending) which is appended to determiners, adjectives, and participles, for multiple forms of all [[Appendix:Glossary#case|grammatical cases]], both singular and plural.}}

=====See also=====
* {{s|plural suffix}} {{l|de|-e}}, {{l|de|-er}}, {{l|de|-s}}

===Etymology 3===
From {{inh|de|gmh|-en}}, from {{inh|de|goh|-īn}}, from {{inh|de|gem-pro|*-īnaz}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alt|de|-n||after ''-er, -el''}}
* {{alt|de|-ern}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|de|/ən/}} {{q|variants as in etymology 1}}

====Suffix====
{{head|de|suffix|cat2=adjective-forming suffixes}}

# {{non-gloss definition|A suffix which is used to create adjectives that most often refer to materials}}
