===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|-y}}, {{m|enm|-i}}, from {{inh|en|ang|-iġ||-y, -ic|pos=suffix}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*-īgaz||-y, -ic}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*-kos}}, {{m|ine-pro|*-ikos}}, {{m|ine-pro|*-iḱos||-y, -ic}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|-ie||-y}}, {{cog|fy|-ich||-y}}, {{cog|nl|-ig||-y}}, {{cog|nds|-ig||-y}}, {{cog|de|-ig||-y}}, {{cog|sv|-ig||-y}}, {{cog|la|-icus||-y, -ic}}, {{cog|grc|-ικός}}, {{cog|sa|-इक}}. {{doublet|en|-ic}}.

====Suffix====
{{en-suffix|cat2=adjective-forming suffixes|cat3=productive suffixes}}

# {{senseid|en|adjectival}} {{n-g|Added to nouns and adjectives to form adjectives meaning “having the quality of”.}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|mess|messy|alt2=mess'''y'''}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|mouse|mousy|alt2=mous'''y'''}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|blue|bluey|alt2=blue'''y'''s}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|clay|clayey|alt2=clay'''ey'''}}
#*{{quote-book
|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9-RC2Gj12SYC&pg=PT60
|title=Down and Out in the Magic Kingdom
|author=[[w:Cory Doctorow|Cory Doctorow]]
|1=en
|publisher=Macmillan
|year=2003
|isbn=9781429972543
|passage=Tim keeps trying to make it all more impressionistic, less computer-'''y'''.}}
# {{n-g|Added to verbs to form adjectives meaning "[[incline]]d to".}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|run|runny|alt2=runn'''y'''}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|stick|sticky|alt2=stick'''y'''}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|fiddle|fiddly|alt2=fiddl'''y'''}}

=====Usage notes=====
* This suffix is very productive and can be added to almost any word. When the resulting word is not perceived to be a real word, a hyphen is often used before the suffix ({{m|en|sandcastle}} → {{m|en||sandcastle-y}}). A few long-established words ending with this suffix have distinctive spellings, such as {{m|en|wintry}} and {{m|en|fiery}}, which English learners might misspell as {{m|en|*wintery}} and {{m|en||*firey}}.

=====Synonyms=====
