=====Usage notes=====
The definite suffix is added to a noun to make it definite. There are four rules for how to apply the definite suffix to a given noun.
# There must be [[w:Agreement (linguistics)|agreement]] between the suffix and the noun, in gender, case and number.
# The suffixed article will lose its ''-i-'' after the short closing vowels ''-a'', ''-i'', and ''-u''. Note that, usually, contraction will happens also after a long closing vowel, but not if it leaves the word [[monosyllabic]].
#: {{sufex|non|arma|altsuf=-inna|armanna}}, from {{m|non|armr|g=m||arm}}
#: {{sufex|non|á|id1=river|altsuf=-ina|ána}}, from {{m|non|á|g=f||river}}
#: {{sufex|non|hesti|altsuf=-inum|hestinum}}, from {{m|non|hestr|g=m||horse}}
#: {{sufex|non|sǫgu|altsuf=-innar|sǫgunnar}}, from {{m|non|saga|g=f||tale}}
#: {{sufex|non|tré|altsuf=-inu|trénu}}, from {{m|non|tré|g=n||tree}}
# In the plural, the suffixed article will lose its ''-i-'' after ''-r''.
#: {{sufex|non|ormar|altsuf=-inir|ormarnir}}, from {{m|non|ormr|g=m||serpent}}
#: {{sufex|non|bœnir|altsuf=-inar|bœnirnar}}, from {{m|non|bœn|g=f||request, prayer}}
#: {{sufex|non|hendr|altsuf=-inar|hendrnar}}, from {{m|non|hǫnd|g=f||hand}}
# In the dative plural, the suffixed article will lose its ''-i-'', and the noun will lose its final ''-m''.
