==Old High German==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|goh|gem-pro|*-ô}}.

====Suffix====
{{head|goh|suffix}}

# {{non-gloss definition|Forms adverbs from adjectives.}}

=====Descendants=====
* {{desc|gmh|-e}}

===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|goh|gem-pro|*-ô}}.
Cognate to {{cog|ang|-a}}, in {{m|ang|ǣta|t=eater}}, {{cog|non|-i}}, {{cog|got|-𐌰}}, in {{m|got|𐌽𐌿𐍄𐌰|t=fisher}}.
In some cases, the root appears in the [[Appendix:Glossary#zero-grade|zero-grade]] as in {{m|goh|boto}} (from {{m|goh|biotan}}).

====Suffix====
{{head|goh|suffix|g=m}}

# {{non-gloss definition|used to form masculine agents from verbs}}
#: {{suffixusex|goh|geban|t1=to give|gëbo|t2=giver}}
#: {{suffixusex|goh|sprehhan|t1=to speak|sprëhho|t2=speaker}}
#: {{suffixusex|goh|biotan|t1=to offer, send, command|boto|t2=messenger}}
#: {{suffixusex|goh|ziohan|t1=to pull, lead|herizogo|t2=army leader}}
#: {{suffixusex|goh|sagēn|t1=to say|fora-sago|t2=prophet}}

=====Declension=====
Most nouns with this suffix follow the n-declension, like {{m|goh|hano|t=cock}}, {{m|goh|namo|t=name}}, {{m|goh|gomo|t=man}}.

=====Descendants=====
* {{desc|gmh|-e}}
** {{desc|de|-e}}

In Middle High German, the suffix is replaced by {{m|gmh|-er}} (whence German {{m|de|-er}}), as in Middle High German {{m|gmh|gëber}} instead of Old High German {{m|goh|gëbo}}.
Only a few German words still have a final ''-e'' that results from Old High German ''-o''.

