==Proto-Indo-European==

===Etymology===
From pre-Indo-European {{m|ine-pro||*méh₂ters}}.

In older literature usually reconstructed de-laryngealized as {{m|ine-pro||*mātēr}} and explained as a combination of a nursery word {{m|ine-pro||*ma|mother}} and the agentive suffix {{m|ine-pro|*-tḗr|*-tēr}}. However, Balto-Slavic forms have acute accent and require a root laryngeal and a short vowel, reflecting *méh₂- (as opposed to *mḗh₂- which would have yielded a circumflexed vowel). Also, no trace of a lengthened grade in the root can be found: in no language did Eichner's law operate (which predicts non-coloration of the *ē in *mḗh₂-tr).

===Noun===
{{ine-noun|f|*méh₂tr-}}

# {{topics|ine-pro|Female family members}} [[mother]]
#: {{syn|ine-pro|*ǵénh₁trih₂}}
#: {{hyper|ine-pro|*ǵénh₁tōr}}

====Inflection====
{{ine-decl-noun-mf|ac=acrostatic|méh₂ter|méh₂tr̥}}

====Reconstruction notes====
There is evidence for both [[suffixal]] and [[radical]] accent:
* Germanic {{m|gem-pro|*mōdēr}} ({{w|Verner's law}}) and Sanskrit {{m|sa|मातृ|माता|tr=mātā́}} show accentuation on the suffix.
* Greek {{m|grc|μήτηρ}} shows accentuation on the root.
* Balto-Slavic is inconclusive (the original accent could have been retracted to the root syllable by {{w|Hirt's law}}).
Only one of these can be the original accentuation, which means that the other must have undergone an analogical accent shift. PIE kinship terms that are semantically closest to “mother” are {{m|ine-pro|*ph₂tḗr||father}} and {{m|ine-pro|*dʰugh₂tḗr||daughter}} and they show in their nominative singular forms accentuation of the suffix, which suggests that the word for “mother” was likely originally accented on the root, shifting its accent to the suffix in some languages under the influence of words for “daughter” and “father”.

The reconstruction of the declension paradigm is similarly problematic:
* Accusative singular forms are Sanskrit {{m|sa||मातरम्|tr=mātáram}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|μητέρα}}, i.&nbsp;e. accented on the suffix only (Lithuanian {{m|lt|móterį}} has radical stress due to {{w|Hirt's law}}).
* Genitive singular forms include Sanskrit {{m|sa||मातुः|tr=mātúḥ}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|μητρός}}, i.&nbsp;e. accented only on the [[desinence]] (Lithuanian {{m|lt|móteres}} has radical stress due to {{w|Hirt's law}}).
From a strictly methodological point of view, this would point to a [[hysterokinetic]] inflection, with the reconstructed accusative singular {{m|ine-pro||*meh₂térm}} and the genitive singular {{m|ine-pro||*meh₂trés}}. However, since the words for “father” and “daughter” appear to have influenced the nominative singular form in some languages, it is possible that the same analogical process occurred in the accusative and genitive singular forms as well.

The conclusive evidence for the original [[acrostatic]] inflection is the Sanskrit ending for the genitive singular in the word {{m|sa||मातुः|tr=mātúḥ}}, which is {{m|sa||-उः}}, the same ending used for other kinship terms: {{m|sa||पितुः|tr=pitúḥ|father|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|sa||दुहितुः|tr=duhitúḥ|daughter|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|sa||भ्रातुः|tr=bhrā́tuḥ|brother|pos=gen. sg.}} etc. This ending can only reflect ''*-C-r-s'', with [[zero-grade]] of the suffix as well as of the ending, which is only possible in an acrostatic paradigm. A similar ending is found in Old Icelandic, where all kinship terms show the ending -or < PIE *-C-r-s, such as {{m|is|fǫðor||father|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|is|móðor||mother|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|is|bróðor||brother|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|is|dóttor||daughter|pos=gen. sg.}}. However, both in Sanskrit and in Old Icelandic this ending is found in ''all'' kinship terms, even in the ones that we know for sure ''not'' to have been acrostatically inflected like {{m|ine-pro|*ph₂tḗr||father}} (genitive {{m|ine-pro||*ph₂tr̥és}} >> Sanskrit {{m|sa||पितुः|tr=pitúḥ}}, Old Icelandic {{m|is||fǫðor}}) and {{m|ine-pro|*dʰugh₂tḗr||daughter}} (genitive {{m|ine-pro||*dʰugtr̥és}} >> Sanskrit {{m|sa||दुहितुः|tr=duhitúḥ}}, Old Icelandic {{m|is||dóttor}}).

It follows that the ending must have spread from some other kinship term. Since PIE {{m|ine-pro|*bʰréh₂tēr||brother}} must have been acrostatically inflected, the endings {{m|sa||-उः}} and ''-or'' must have been original in this word ({{m|ine-pro||*bʰréh₂tr̥s}} >> Sanskrit {{m|sa||भ्रातुः|tr=bhrā́tuḥ}}, Old Icelandic {{m|is||bróðor}}). Since it appears unlikely that the ending {{m|ine-pro||*-r-s}} would have spread so vastly (even to the word for “father”) solely on the basis of the word for “brother”, we must assume that the ending was also present in another kinship term, namely the word for “mother”, which was (as explained above) in its nominative singular form radically stressed, which would fit the acrostatic accentuation pattern, being the source of this genitive singular ending {{m|ine-pro||*-r-s}}.

