===Etymology 2===
Said by some to be from the idea that when one does a thing “for love”, that is for no monetary gain, the word “love” implies "nothing". The previously held belief that it originated from the {{der|en|fr|-}} term {{m|fr|œuf|l’œuf|t=the egg}}, due to its shape, is no longer widely accepted, though compare the use of [[duck]] (reputed to be short for duck's egg) for a zero score at cricket.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{lb|en|racquet sports|billiards}} [[zero|Zero]], no score.
#: ''So that’s fifteen-'''love''' to Kournikova.''
#* '''2013''', {{w|Paul McNamee}}, ''Game Changer: My Tennis Life''
#*: The next day [[w:Andre Agassi|Agassi]] came back from two sets to '''love''' down to beat Courier in five sets.
# Nothing; no recompense. <!--see Hotten's Slang Dictionary 1873-->
#* '''1916''', H. Rider Haggard, ''The Ivory Child''
#*: I fought the white man for less than sixpence. I fought him for '''love''', which is nothing at all.

