==Latin==

===Etymology===
{{root|la|ine-pro|*deh₃-}}
From {{inh|la|itc-pro|*didō}}, from {{inh|la|ine-pro|*dédeh₃ti}}, from the root {{m|ine-pro|*deh₃-||give}}. The reduplication was lost in Latin in the present tense, but is preserved in the other Italic languages. A root aorist (from {{cog|ine-pro|*déh₃t}}) is preserved in Venetic {{m|xve|𐌆𐌏𐌕𐌏}}; the other Italic perfect forms reflect a reduplicated stative, {{m|itc-pro|*dedai}}. However, the root aorist possibly served as the source of the Latin present forms.<ref>{{R:itc:EDL}}</ref>

Cognates include {{cog|grc|δίδωμι}}, {{cog|sa|ददाति|tr=dádāti}}, {{cog|peo|sc=Xpeo|𐎭𐎭𐎠𐎬𐎢𐎺|tr=dā-}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{la-IPA|dō}}
* {{audio|la|la-cls-do.ogg|Audio (Classical)}}

===Verb===
{{la-verb|irreg|dō}}

# I [[give]]
#: {{syn|la|dōnō}}
#: {{ux|la|Tertium non '''datur'''.''<sup>{{w|law of excluded middle}}</sup>''|A third [possibility] is not '''given''': <math> P \or \neg P </math>.}}
#* {{Q|la|Jerome|Vulgate|Exodus|20|12|quote=Honora patrem tuum et matrem tuam, ut sis longaevus super terram, quam Dominus Deus tuus '''dabit''' tibi.|trans=Honour thy father and thy mother: that thy days may be long upon the land which the LORD thy God '''giveth''' thee.}}
# I [[impart]], [[offer]], [[render]], [[present]] with
#: {{syn|la|afferō}}
#* '''c. 200 BC''', {{w|Plautus}} ''{{w|Captivi}}'' ("the captives") ([https://web.archive.org/web/20130113120403/http://www.ihaystack.com/authors/m/plautus_titus_maccius/00016564_amphitryo_asinaria_aulularia_bacchides_captivi_amphi/00016564_englishlatin_utf8_p043.htm English and Latin text])
#*: {{ux|la|'''Do''' tibi operam, Aristophontes, si quid est quod me velis.|I’m at your service, Aristophontes, if there’s anything you want of me. ("I '''offer''' labour to you, Aristophontes…)}}
#* {{Q|la|[[w:Titus Livius|Titus Livius]]|[[w:Ab Urbe Condita Libri|Ab Urbe Condita]]|I, 14|quote={{l-lite|la|causam}} {{l-lite|la|minus}} {{l-lite|la|mirabilem}} '''dedit'''|t=[[w:Romulus|he]] '''rendered''' the circumstances less strange}}
# I [[afford]], [[grant]]
#: {{syn|la|dōnō}}
#* {{Q|la|Marcus Tullius Cicero|{{w|Philippicae|Philippics}}|, 1.22.7|year=44 BCE|quote=Non igitur provocatio ista lege '''datur''', sed duae maxime salutares leges quaestionesque tolluntur. Quid est aliud hortari adulescentis ut turbulenti, ut seditiosi, ut perniciosi cives velint esse?|trans=It is not, therefore, a right of appeal that is '''afforded''' by that law, but two most salutary laws and modes of judicial investigation that are abolished. And what is this but exhorting young men to be turbulent, seditious, mischievous citizens?}}
#* {{Q|la|Marcus Tullius Cicero|{{w|Philippicae|Philippics}}|, 1.23.4|year=44 BCE|quote=Quid, quod obrogatur legibus Cæsaris, quae iubent ei qui de vi itemque	ei qui maiestatis damnatus sit aqua et igni interdici? quibus cum provocatio '''datur''', nonne acta Cæsaris rescinduntur?	Quae quidem ego, patres conscripti, qui illa numquam probavi, tamen ita conservanda concordiae causa arbitratus sum ut non modo, quas vivus leges Cæsar tulisset, infirmandas hoc tempore non putarem, sed ne illas quidem quas post mortem Cæsaris prolatas esse et fixas videtis.|trans=What more? Is not this a substitution of a new law for the laws of Cæsar, which enact that every man who has been convicted of violence, and also every man who has been convicted of treason, shall be interdicted from fire and water? And, when those men have a right of appeal '''granted''' them, are not the acts of Cæsar rescinded? And those acts, O conscript fathers, I, who never approved of them, have still thought it advisable to maintain for the sake of concord; so that I not only did not think that the laws which Cæsar had passed in his lifetime ought to be repealed, but I did not approve of meddling with those even which since the death of Cæsar you have seen produced and published.}}
# I [[bestow]], [[confer]] (''on'' or ''upon'')
#: {{syn|la|dōnō}}
# I [[concede]], [[surrender]], [[yield]]
# I [[put]]
# I [[adduce]] {{gloss|e.g., a witness}}

====Conjugation====
In Vulgar Latin, ''dō'' becomes ''*dao'', by analogy with the root vowel ''-a-'', but also by some elided third conjugation verbs like ''*vao'', ''*vare'' (< {{m-lite|la|vado|vadō, vadere}}). 

This table includes an archaic present subjunctive conjugation on a ''du-'' root that appears in the works of Plautus and Terence.
