====Noun====
{{en-noun|fair}}

# Something which is fair (in various senses of the adjective).
#: {{ux|en|When will we learn to distinguish between the '''fair''' and the foul?}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[woman]], a member of the ‘[[fair sex]]’; also as a collective singular, [[women]].
#* '''1744''', {{w|Georg Friedrich Händel}}, ''[[:w:Hercules (Handel)|Hercules]]'', act 2, scene 8
#*: Love and Hymen, hand in hand, / Come, restore the nuptial band! / And sincere delights prepare / To crown the hero and the '''fair'''.
#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|passage=Here Jones, having ordered a servant to show a room above stairs, was ascending, when the dishevelled '''fair''', hastily following, was laid hold on by the master of the house, who cried, “Heyday, where is that beggar wench going? Stay below stairs, I desire you.”}}
#* {{RQ:Byron Don Juan|III|24|text=If single, probably his plighted '''Fair''' / Has in his absence wedded some rich miser {{nb...}}.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[fairness|Fairness]], beauty.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Comedy of Errors|2|1|passage=My decayed '''fair'''}}
# A fair woman; a sweetheart.
#* '''1743''', {{w|William Shenstone}}, ''A Pastoral Ballad''
#*: I have found out a gift for my '''fair'''.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Good fortune; good luck.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Taming of the Shrew|V|ii|text=Now, '''fair''' befall thee, good Petruchio!}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{senseid|en|to smooth}} {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[smoothen]] or [[even]] a [[surface]] (especially a [[connection]] or [[junction]] on a surface).
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To bring into perfect [[alignment]] (especially about [[rivet]] [[hole]]s when connecting structural members).
# {{lb|en|transitive|art}} To make an [[animation]] [[smooth]], removing any [[jerkiness]].
#* '''1996''', ''Computer Animation '96: June 3-4, 1996, Geneva, Switzerland'' (page 136)
#*: Since the sequence of data contain sampling noises, the captured motion is not smooth and wiggles along the moving path. There are well-known '''fairing''' algorithms in Euclidean space based on difference geometry.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To construct or design with the aim of producing a smooth outline or reducing [[air]] [[drag]] or water resistance.
#* '''1920''', ''Technical Report of the Advisory Committee for Aeronautics'' (page 206)
#*: Two forward cars were provided with the model. One of these (shown detached in Fig. 1) was '''faired''' at its after end, with a view to possible reduction of head resistance, and to induce a better flow of air to the propeller.
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To make fair or beautiful.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Sonnets|sonnet=123|passage='''Fairing''' the foul with art’s false borrow’d face}}

