==English==
{{was wotd|2020|October|30}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰeh₁-}}
From Late {{inh|en|enm|thesis|t=lowering of the voice}}<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=thē̆sis|pos=n|id=MED45219}}</ref> and also borrowed directly from its {{glossary|etymon}} {{bor|en|la|thesis|t=proposition, thesis; lowering of the voice}}, from {{der|en|grc|θέσῐς|t=arrangement, placement, setting; conclusion, position, thesis; lowering of the voice}}, from {{m|grc|τῐ́θημῐ|t=to place, put, set; to put down in writing; to consider as, regard}}<ref name="OED">{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=200655|date=1912}}</ref><ref>{{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref> (ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*dʰeh₁-|t=to do; to place, put}}) + {{m|grc|-σῐς|pos={{glossary|suffix}} forming {{glossary|abstract noun}}s or {{glossary|noun}}s of action, process, or result}}. The English word is a {{doublet|en|deed|nocap=1}}.

Sense 1.1 (“proposition or statement supported by arguments”) is adopted from {{m|en|antithesis}}.<ref name="OED"/> Sense 1.4 (“initial stage of reasoning”) was first used by the German philosopher {{w|Johann Gottlieb Fichte}} (1762–1814), and later applied to the [[dialectical]] [[method]] of his countryman, the philosopher {{w|Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel}} (1770–1831).

The {{glossary|plural}} form {{m|en|theses}} is borrowed from {{bor|en|la|thesēs}}, from {{der|en|grc|θέσεις}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{glossary|Singular}}:
** {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈθiːsɪs/|/ˈθɛsɪs/|qual2=archaic}}
** {{audio|en|en-uk-thesis.oga|Audio (RP)}}
** {{a|GA}} {{IPA|en|/ˈθisɪs/}}
** {{audio|en|en-us-thesis.ogg|Audio (GA)}}
** {{rhymes|en|iːsɪs|s=2}}
** {{hyph|en|the|sis}}
* {{glossary|Plural}}:
** {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈθiːsiːz/}}
** {{audio|en|en-uk-theses.ogg|Audio (RP)}}
** {{a|GA}} {{IPA|en|/ˈθisiz/}}
** {{rhymes|en|iːsiːz}}
** {{hyph|en|the|ses}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|theses}}

# {{non-gloss definition|Senses relating to logic, rhetoric, etc.}}
## {{lb|en|rhetoric}} A [[proposition]] or [[statement]] [[support#Verb|supported]] by [[argument]]s.
## {{lb|en|by extension}} A [[lengthy]] [[essay]] [[write|written]] to [[establish]] the [[validity]] of a thesis ''(sense 1.1)'', especially one [[submit]]ted in order to complete the requirements for a non-[[doctoral]] [[degree]] in the US and a doctoral degree in the UK; a [[dissertation]].
##* {{RQ:Goldsmith Vicar of Wakefield|volume=II|chapter=The Conclusion|pages=218–219|pageref=218|passage=I told them of the grave, becoming, and ſublime deportment they ſhould aſſume upon this myſtical occaſion, and read them two homilies and a '''theſis''' of my own compoſing, in order to prepare them.}}
## {{lb|en|mathematics|computer science}} A [[conjecture]], especially one too vague to be formally stated or verified but useful as a working convention.
## {{lb|en|logic}} An [[affirmation]], or [[distinction]] from a [[supposition]] or [[hypothesis]].
## {{lb|en|philosophy}} In the [[dialectical]] [[method]] of {{w|Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel}}: the [[initial#Adjective|initial]] [[stage#Noun|stage]] of [[reasoning#Noun|reasoning]] where a [[formal#Adjective|formal]] statement of a [[point#Noun|point]] is [[develop]]ed; this is [[follow]]ed by [[antithesis]] and [[synthesis]].
# {{non-gloss definition|Senses relating to music and prosody.}}
## {{lb|en|music|prosody|originally}} The [[action]] of [[lower#Verb|lowering]] the [[hand#Noun|hand]] or bringing down the [[foot#Noun|foot]] when [[indicate|indicating]] a [[rhythm]]; hence, an [[accented#Adjective|accented]] [[part#Noun|part]] of a [[measure#Noun|measure]] of [[music]] or [[verse#Noun|verse]] indicated by this action; an [[ictus]], a [[stress#Noun|stress]].
##: {{antonym|en|arsis}}
## {{lb|en|music|prosody|with a reversal of meaning}} A [[depression]] of the [[voice#Noun|voice]] when [[pronounce|pronouncing]] a [[syllable]]s of a [[word#Noun|word]]; hence, the [[unstressed]] part of the [[metrical foot]] of a verse upon which such a depression [[fall#Verb|falls]], or an [[unaccented]] [[musical#Adjective|musical]] [[note#Noun|note]].

