#*: I often mused on what the politicians or authorities would say if they could see for themselves the horrendous consequences of someone who’d been '''glassed''', or viciously assaulted.
#* '''2003,''' Mark Sturdy, ''Pulp'' [http://books.google.com/books?ie=UTF-8&hl=en&id=sdF52lBdu3AC&pg=PA139&lpg=PA139&sig=o2nzWpBQX4v0Csr5DLGgTJrCy5c page 139]:
#*: One night he was in this nightclub in Sheffield and he got '''glassed''' by this bloke who’d been just let out of prison that day.
# {{lb|en|transitive|science fiction}} To [[bombard]] an area with such intensity ([[nuclear bomb]], [[fusion bomb]], etc) as to [[melt]] the [[landscape]] into glass.
#* '''2012''', ''Halo: First Strike,'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=DmdFf5PnB4wC&pg=PA190&dq=glass#v=onepage page 190]:
#*: “The Covenant don’t ‘miss’ anything when they '''glass''' a planet,” the Master Chief replied.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To view through an optical instrument such as binoculars.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=Ben D. Mahaffey|title=50 Years of Hunting and Fishing|page=95|passage=Andy took his binoculars and '''glassed''' the area below.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[smooth]] or [[polish]] (leather, etc.), by rubbing it with a glass [[burnisher]].
# {{lb|en|archaic|reflexive}} To [[reflect]]; to [[mirror]].
#* {{RQ:Motley Dutch Republic|passage=Happy to '''glass''' themselves in so brilliant a mirror.}}
#* {{RQ:Byron Childe Harold|canto=IV|stanza=LXXXIII|passage=Where the Almighty's form '''glasses''' itself in tempests.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make [[glassy]].
